data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)  →  specific count check covers this
    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)  →  gives "expected 3, got N" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))  →  loop gives per-item failure messages
    foreach (var user in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User '{user.Name}' is not active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)  →  says "is null" instead of "is not true"
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key MSTest assertions for collections:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `IsTrue(x.Count == n)` | `AreEqual(n, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual |
| `IsTrue(x != null)` | `IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer failure message |
| `IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` | Says what was missing |
| — | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` | Same items, any order |
| — | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(list)` | No nulls in collection |
| — | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(list)` | No duplicates |

The main win: when a test fails, `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` tells you *"expected 3 but got 5"* while `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count == 3)` just says *"expected true, got false"*.
